00:03:14.880 --> 00:03:15.880
Well, how do they work?

00:03:15.880 --> 00:03:21.320
Well, there's some basic components that they need to do.

00:03:21.320 --> 00:03:25.779
So one is that your Dashboard, whatever software is running your Dashboard, it needs to fetch

00:03:25.779 --> 00:03:29.080
the data somehow.

00:03:29.080 --> 00:03:32.960
That seems pretty obvious, but you need to get the data, and that can sometimes be hard

00:03:32.960 --> 00:03:34.520
work.

00:03:34.520 --> 00:03:41.320
Then you process and summarize the data, and we all know that R is really good for this.

00:03:41.320 --> 00:03:44.600
And concisely present the process data, often this involves visualization, there's summary

00:03:44.600 --> 00:03:52.639
tables, and optionally we can provide exploration tools if that's the type of Dashboard that

00:03:52.639 --> 00:03:55.360
we're working on.

00:03:55.360 --> 00:04:02.399
Okay, so fetching the data, when you're, in general when you're creating a Dashboard and

00:04:02.399 --> 00:04:04.759
you're grabbing the data, it has to be done quickly.

00:04:04.759 --> 00:04:10.039
If you, you know, if it takes a minute for you to grab your data from your data source,

00:04:10.039 --> 00:04:15.720
that's generally not an acceptable wait for most users.

00:04:15.720 --> 00:04:21.600
So if you have a small data set, relatively small data set, that's usually not a problem.

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:22.600
There's many different ways to do this.

00:04:22.600 --> 00:04:28.739
You can grab it using, from a database, using the DBI package, there's many other R packages

00:04:28.739 --> 00:04:33.019
for database, interfacing with databases as well.

00:04:33.019 --> 00:04:37.940
You could schedule some data dumps or data summaries, like nightly, if that's, you know,

00:04:37.940 --> 00:04:43.220
if that's the frequency that is appropriate for your data, writing it to a file, and then

00:04:43.220 --> 00:04:48.480
your Dashboard can read in a CSV or summarized, or a summarized data set.

00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:54.420
Or maybe you have like a web API that you can just visit a web URL and it'll return

00:04:54.420 --> 00:04:56.519
data in JSON or XML.

00:04:56.519 --> 00:05:02.559
So there's great R packages for grabbing those as well, JSON Lite and XML.

00:05:02.559 --> 00:05:09.200
And Hadley Wickham, our chief scientist at RStudio, is working on a new XML package for

00:05:09.200 --> 00:05:13.160
working with XML data, which should make it easier and faster.

00:05:13.160 --> 00:05:18.559
So again, you know, if you've got a really large data set and you need to, and it takes

00:05:18.559 --> 00:05:25.079
too long to fetch that data, you can summarize it on a scheduled basis and then grab that

00:05:25.079 --> 00:05:29.760
summarized data in your Dashboard.

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:35.519
So for presenting data using Shiny, there's all sorts of, there's different types of outputs.

00:05:35.519 --> 00:05:39.920
You can output numbers and text, you can output tables, you can output graphs, and these are

00:05:39.920 --> 00:05:45.000
some of the function names that are available in Shiny for doing these things.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:48.959
And I'll show some examples of this in a bit.

00:05:49.959 --> 00:05:53.559
Finally, well there's components for exploration.

00:05:53.559 --> 00:05:59.799
So in Shiny, you know, so far I've talked about how data comes out to you, and if you

00:05:59.799 --> 00:06:04.839
want people to be able to explore their data, they need to have, you need to have inputs.

00:06:04.839 --> 00:06:11.239
So the user needs to be able to send information to the Dashboard, you know, then their client,

00:06:11.239 --> 00:06:16.279
which is a web browser, to the server, which is running R. And there's very, these are

00:06:16.279 --> 00:06:20.359
mostly pretty standard web inputs.

00:06:20.359 --> 00:06:24.239
There's a text input box, there's a slider, that's, well that's not totally a standard

00:06:24.239 --> 00:06:26.440
thing, but we have that.

00:06:26.440 --> 00:06:30.600
Select inputs, checkboxes, radio buttons, buttons, data inputs, all sorts of things

00:06:30.600 --> 00:06:36.920
like that that Shiny provides for exploring your data, for getting user input to explore

00:06:36.920 --> 00:06:40.640
the data.

00:06:40.640 --> 00:06:44.600
And we're also working on some new interactive components.

00:06:44.600 --> 00:06:48.839
These are some R packages, there's one called, we're working on called DT, which provides

00:06:48.839 --> 00:06:56.799
interactive tables that you can sort and filter interactively, so they both will display data

00:06:56.799 --> 00:07:01.559
from the server, and they can also accept input from the client.

00:07:01.559 --> 00:07:05.320
There's Leaflet, which is used for making interactive maps, and we're going to see a

00:07:05.320 --> 00:07:07.480
bit of that later.

00:07:07.480 --> 00:07:12.519
And you can, we're also adding features to allow interactions with base R graphics and

00:07:12.920 --> 00:07:17.359
ggplot2, and we'll see that as well.

