00:07:33.600 --> 00:07:35.559
So what is Shiny?

00:07:35.559 --> 00:07:40.839
So Shiny is an R package that we're developing at RStudio.

00:07:40.839 --> 00:07:47.640
It's a platform for creating web applications in R, and it uses a reactive programming model,

00:07:47.640 --> 00:07:54.799
which makes it really easy for application developers to use their existing R knowledge

00:07:54.799 --> 00:08:00.760
to create interactive applications, you don't have to know about all sorts of complex underlying

00:08:00.760 --> 00:08:06.480
stuff like callbacks, and all of that is sort of abstracted away, so you can just, you can

00:08:06.480 --> 00:08:10.959
write this like you're writing regular R code, or almost like that.

00:08:10.959 --> 00:08:11.959
And it's free software.

00:08:11.959 --> 00:08:16.119
It's licensed under the GPL version 3.

00:08:16.119 --> 00:08:22.720
Okay, now here's some code for a Shiny application.

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:24.640
Every Shiny application has, there's two sides of it.

00:08:24.640 --> 00:08:31.160
There's the user interface, which is this HTML code for generating a webpage, and there's

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:38.440
the server code, which is R code for running your analyses and generating outputs.

00:08:38.440 --> 00:08:42.280
So let me see if I can run this here.

00:08:42.280 --> 00:08:47.359
Let's find my RStudio session.

00:08:47.359 --> 00:08:51.599
Zoom in a little bit.

00:08:51.599 --> 00:08:54.159
Okay so I'm running this application.

00:08:54.159 --> 00:08:55.159
This is really basic.

00:08:55.159 --> 00:08:58.119
It doesn't do anything particularly sophisticated.

00:08:58.119 --> 00:09:03.039
There's a slider that determines how many random points are in this scatter plot here,

00:09:03.039 --> 00:09:13.640
so I can bump it up to, that's 468, 27, and when I move this slider, this plot updates.

00:09:13.640 --> 00:09:17.080
How do we actually implement that?

00:09:17.080 --> 00:09:26.119
Well, there's, as you saw, the user interface, there's a slider input, which takes in some

00:09:26.119 --> 00:09:31.840
value, and there's a plot output, which displays the plot on the webpage.

00:09:31.840 --> 00:09:39.159
And on the server side, there's this render plot, which, this is, the render plot runs

00:09:39.159 --> 00:09:45.599
the code inside of it, it runs the plot function that's in base R, and it captures that output

00:09:45.599 --> 00:09:48.479
and sends it to, back to the client.

00:09:48.479 --> 00:09:55.280
So the important things to find these relationships are right here.

00:09:55.440 --> 00:09:56.440
I've highlighted them.

00:09:56.440 --> 00:10:04.239
So N, slider input is N, and when the user updates that value, it causes the input dollar

00:10:04.239 --> 00:10:10.479
N and the server side code to be updated, and when these values change, Shiny knows

00:10:10.479 --> 00:10:12.640
that this render plot needs to be re-executed.

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:20.479
So it does that, saves the output to the disk plot, and that gets sent back to the client.

00:10:20.479 --> 00:10:28.760
So within the server side code, you're almost writing regular R code.

00:10:28.760 --> 00:10:37.239
And the UI, there's, Shiny has a bunch of constructs for generating these webpages.

00:10:37.239 --> 00:10:44.239
These three functions, basic page, slider input, and plot output, those generate HTML,

00:10:44.239 --> 00:10:46.440
and that HTML gets sent to the client.

00:10:47.440 --> 00:10:52.880
And then finally, we have the UI and the server, and we put them together in a Shiny app object.

00:10:52.880 --> 00:10:59.599
Now if you're familiar with Shiny and you're just using a UI.R file and a server.R file,

00:10:59.599 --> 00:11:06.080
this is a way of creating apps with just a single file, which is, there's some advantages

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:10.840
to it, it's, you can just cut and paste the code and run it in the terminal like I did,

00:11:10.840 --> 00:11:13.739
or in the R console, and it just works.

00:11:13.739 --> 00:11:16.500
You don't have to go and create a directory and create all these files to make, to run

00:11:16.500 --> 00:11:17.500
your application.

00:11:17.500 --> 00:11:22.099
So it's convenient in that respect.

00:11:22.099 --> 00:11:25.700
Okay, so that's the real basics of Shiny.

