00:15:36.059 --> 00:15:40.140
Now how do those boxes know to be the right width?

00:15:40.140 --> 00:15:47.900
Well, to understand that, we have to understand the bootstrap grid a little bit.

00:15:47.900 --> 00:15:55.580
In bootstrap, there's a layout using grids of rows and columns.

00:15:55.580 --> 00:15:59.780
Now you add rows, it's a row first, you add a row, and then each row has 12 columns, and

00:15:59.780 --> 00:16:04.739
then HTML elements, like these boxes, can occupy any number of the 12 columns.

00:16:04.739 --> 00:16:12.700
So the boxes by default take up six spaces, so you can put two of them side by side.

00:16:12.700 --> 00:16:21.219
And if you have, you can have three columns here, fluid row, three columns with four,

00:16:21.219 --> 00:16:27.419
you can have differently sized columns, three, six, three, or four and eight, if you want

00:16:27.419 --> 00:16:31.460
different sized boxes.

00:16:31.460 --> 00:16:37.739
And so, I just want to mention, don't forget your columns.

00:16:37.739 --> 00:16:43.700
If you have a row and you don't put a column in it, then you'll end up with text that's

00:16:43.700 --> 00:16:51.979
like, or HTML components that are butting up against the edge there, and that's usually

00:16:51.979 --> 00:16:53.700
not what you want.

00:16:53.700 --> 00:17:00.700
With the column, there's a little bit of margin there, so it doesn't touch the edge there.

00:17:00.700 --> 00:17:07.719
